{"key":"post-12728864","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12728864</id>\n<content>All of the above is correct and just to add, the intensity of light is reduced by the square of the distance as you move the light away.&amp;nbsp; In other words if you move a light from 12&quot; away from the tub to 24&quot; away, you cut the light to 1/4 the amount.&amp;nbsp; If you move it from 12&quot; away to 36&quot; away, you cut the amount of light to 1/9 what it was before.&amp;nbsp; That's why you want the light as close as you can without causing excess heat buildup.&amp;nbsp; Light from the sides is just as good as light from above.&amp;nbsp; In fact, the sides of a terrarium in the middle of a room can bring in much more light, considering they're 80% of the surface area, vs only 20% for the top.(assuming the tub is a cube for simplicity).&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12728889</next>\n<prev>12728707</prev>\n<first>12728443</first>\n<last>12731011</last>\n<when>1276316426</when>\n<utime>06/12/10 07:20 AM</utime>\n</post>"}